🔧 Network Infrastructure Deployment – Ebikane Farm:

I recently participated in a network infrastructure installation project at Ebikane Farm, connecting the Control Center, Administrative Building, and other operational units to establish reliable communication and network connectivity across the facility.

This project involved structured Ethernet cabling, underground optical fiber deployment, rack installation, and wireless access point configuration to ensure stable and scalable network coverage.

📡 Project Breakdown

1: Underground Optical Fiber Backbone

- Deployed underground optical fiber cable from the Control Center to the Administrative building.

- Routed the fiber safely through protective channels to prevent environmental damage.

- Terminated and tested the fiber link to ensure high-speed backbone connectivity between buildings.

2: Rooftop Network Distribution

- Extended connectivity from the underground fiber to the Administrative building roof.

- Installed Ethernet cabling from the roof down to the network rack cabinet where core equipment is organized.

- Ensured proper cable routing and protection to maintain signal integrity.

3: Rack Cabinet & Network Equipment Setup

- Mounted and organized network devices inside the server rack cabinet.

- Implemented proper patching and cable management for easy maintenance and troubleshooting.

4: Wireless Access Point Installation

- Installed Access Points (APs) on the ceiling to provide wireless coverage across the building.

- Carefully positioned the APs to ensure stable signal distribution and optimal coverage.

- Connected the APs through Ethernet cabling and PoE power delivery.

5: Ethernet Cabling and Internal Wiring

- Installed Ethernet cables linking network devices from the rack cabinet to the access points.

- During installation we worked with the twisted internal conductors used in Ethernet cabling:

 - Brown pair – carries electrical power used to power the access point.

 - Red conductor – used for network signal transmission.

 - Blue conductor – serves as neutral/return in the wiring arrangement.


🛠 Tools & Equipment Used

- Cable ripper / cutter for preparing Ethernet cables

- Crimping tools for RJ45 termination

- Gigabit PoE injectors

- Wireless Access Points

- Optical fiber cable

- Ethernet LAN cables

- Network rack cabinet

📉 Outcome
The completed deployment created a stable hybrid network infrastructure combining fiber backbone, structured cabling, and wireless networking, enabling seamless connectivity between the control unit, administrative center, and operational areas at Ebikane Farm.

Projects like this demonstrate how proper cabling structure, fiber deployment, and wireless network design are essential for building reliable IT environments.
